TY  - JOUR
AU  - Frank, Murray Z.
T1  - An Intertemporal Model of Industrial Exit*
PY  - 1988
Y1  - 1988/05/01
DO  - 10.2307/1885116
JO  - The Quarterly Journal of Economics
JA  - Q J Econ
VL  - 103
IS  - 2
SP  - 333
EP  - 344
SN  - 0033-5533
AB  - A finite horizon model of industrial exit is developed. After an initial lag, most exits are by young firms. The duration of the lag is positively related to sunk entry costs, but not due to the fallacy of sunk costs. The conception of entry differs from previous research; as a result, not all entrants are identical; and firm size affects the rate of learning. On average, larger new firms last longer. Entrepreneurs in declining firms act more lazily as the firm declines. A number of empirical observations about declining firms are organized by the model.
Y2  - 3/25/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.2307/1885116
ER  - 



